(2, 'Mega V2 UPS', '<h1>Modular UPS (Uninterrupted Power Supply)</h1>\n\n<p>Modular UPS architecture (or topology) is a method designed to reduce cost and give UPS users flexibility in system configuration and use. Modular UPS systems consists of fixed control and power switching modules. The battery storage element is modularized. Typical systems are designed to fit into one rack. Larger UPS system designed for large IT installations span multiple racks and consists of dozens to hundreds of modules. Battery storage &ldquo;modules&rdquo; are configured from one to as many as ten modules in typical medium size UPS system. Each battery &ldquo;module&rdquo; gives a fixed power storage capacity. Gamatronics&rsquo; Mega V2 Modular UPS system, is configured in one to twenty (20) battery modules. This gives the system a power capacity range of 25 kVA to 500 kVA (i.e. kW).</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Key Architectural Features:</h2>\n\n<p><img alt="Modular UPS Block Diagram Scheme" src="http://www.gamatronic.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/modular-ups-block-diagram-scheme.png" style="float:right; height:285px; margin:0px 0px 0px 10px; width:364px" />Modular UPS architecture is made up of two main components: control and connectivity sub-system, and a modular storage sub-system. The control and connectivity sub-system is standard and serves the same function in most UPS products. The modular storage sub-system, is unique in the ability to &ldquo;assemble&rdquo; (or install) as many battery storage modules as needed (determined by the power capacity in use). In most systems, maximum number of modules is ten to twenty. Very large systems, or systems which can be connected together, the number of modules can run in the hundreds.</p>\n\n<h2>Design and operational features:</h2>\n\n<p>Modular UPS systems uses simple architecture to reduce cost and enhance operational flexibility. UPS users starting out, can design a minimal system with simple expansion capability. Installations with a single system enjoy the ability to expand the UPS capacity in small increments, therefore reducing initial cost. Incremental expansion also enable the operators to test system capacity.</p>\n\n<p>In installations where multiple UPS systems are used, modular configuration can be shared among different systems. Here each system can be expanded or reduced in capacity as needed. Spare battery modules are shared among systems, reducing operational costs and increasing backup resiliency. Finally, modular systems enable quick operational configuration changes as needed.</p>\n\n<h2>Configuration and operation benefits:</h2>\n\n<p>Modular UPS products have exceptional benefits in configuration and operation. Configuring a modular UPS system at the initial installation, gives an IT manager the ability to buy and install a small capacity system without giving up on expansion in the future. A small system not only gives a new installation cost saving advantage, it also makes for a simple qualification and operational testing. If the UPS system is new to the installation, users can test it&rsquo;s usefulness, qualify it&rsquo;s capabilities, and assure the system is correctly installed for the desired backup function. If the UPS system is a new model or represent a change in supplier, the initial cost is low and so is the initial resource allocation (space, installation manpower, and qualification time and cost.)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>In the operational realm, a small configuration system is useful in testing the effectiveness and overall operational capabilities of the UPS. Effectiveness testing may take time and put some operational systems at risk of crashing or at least interrupting regular operation. With a small system, this can be done on a non-business critical function or at off-peak hours (i.e. weekend or system backup period). In critical business operations, UPS qualification, testing and configuration, post installation, is a critical IT maintenance task. A small modular UPS system gives IT operators the ability to test a small system on any sub-system or none business-critical component of a large operation (i.e. a redundant server or storage component). By using the UPS this way the first few times, IT staff can characterize a power backup operation and become familiar with it&rsquo;s capabilities. If testing and configuration beyond installation needs to be performed on multiple systems, one modular UPS sub-system can serve multiple tests, time and time again. This makes for a more effective, economic, and functional installation of the UPS.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Convenience and effectiveness in large multi-UPS installations:</h2>\n\n<p><img alt="Modular UPS - Functional Front View- 500kVA" src="http://www.gamatronic.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/modular-ups-functional-front-view-500kVA.png" style="float:right; height:285px; margin:0px 0px 0px 10px; width:364px" />In today&rsquo;s fiercely competitive IT service delivery landscape, UPS use is a critical element is a manager&rsquo;s tool box. It gives IT departments, even whole companies, a competitive edge that can not be over emphasized. IT services organizations, rely on UPS sub-systems to give customers a transparent ever present compute and networking service. Therefore, many mission critical operations install UPS systems on all their critical servers, storage, data center and networking equipment. This usually means configuration of multiple UPS sub-systems of different size. Here, modular UPS systems are extremely useful. By standardizing on one type of system (the same product model for the whole installation), IT operators can configure power capacity needs&nbsp;<em>&ldquo;on the fly&rdquo;</em>. Operators can change power configurations on each system instance at any time, move battery modules and test their effectiveness with capacity change, and keep a small set of spare power modules for all the UPS systems (instead of multiple / different spares). In case of disaster or failure of a UPS system, operators can swap battery and controller modules as needed assuring that key operational features are always have protection&nbsp;from power failure (prioritize network service over storage, etc.) This makes for an additional level of operational integrity. It gives IT staff and management flexibility and capability available to every other component in an IT services&rsquo; installation. Now, UPS and power management is as manageable as virtual processors, virtual storage and hot swappable networking equipment. This should be good news to any organization and music to the IT operator&rsquo;s ears.</p>\n\n<h2>Modular UPS -&nbsp;The Benefits of Modularity</h2>\n\n<p>The modular UPS first entered the market approximately a decade ago. One may ask, why only then? What aroused consumers initial objections? And finally for what reasons are these systems highly acclaimed for today? This article attempts to shed light on these issues from commercial and technical aspects.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3>The History of Modular UPS</h3>\n\n<p>The modular UPS did not spring out of thin air; it was enabled by technological advancements. The three phase UPS which was prevalent in the 90&rsquo;s was mainly based on: 6 or 12 pulse rectifiers with thyristors, PWM inverters with IGBT components (fast high performance power transistors) and output transformers, necessary for the inverter technology.<br />\nThe rectifier included big chokes for the purpose of improving performance. These chokes and transformers outlined the measure and weight of the systems. The transformer-less technology and shift to rectifiers with PFC technology, allowed the systems to be dramatically smaller. The use of advanced technology assisted in the creation of a three phase UPS with the output power of 10,000 VA that weighed 9 Kg only. Compare this UPS to the previous one&rsquo;s that weighed over 100 Kg, this was a remarkable advancement.<br />\nSeveral UPS manufacturers throughout the world realized the potential and immediately began to implement the new technologies. They did not rest with upgrading the existing systems, but rather opted for further advancement &ndash; building a brand new modular system.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3>Resistance to modularity?</h3>\n\n<p>One can understand customer&rsquo;s initial hesitation towards modular technology raised from the fears of transformer-less technology. For years&nbsp;<a href="http://www.gamatronic.com/category/products/ups-systems/">UPS systems</a>&nbsp;were based on inverter with transformer, suddenly consumers were told that the new system which comprised of transformer-less inverter would work even better than before. Today this might sound odd, but at the time, most electrical consultants would testify that the system was better with a transformer. Among other things they claimed that the advantages of a transformer-based UPS are that the load (output current) is completely separated from the utility power (input current) by a method known as galvanic isolation. It also completely eliminates all direct current to the load which can be harmful to it.</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3>Benefits of the Modular UPS</h3>\n\n<p>Manufacturers invested a lot of effort to show case the positive aspects of the product. These include:</p>\n\n<ul style="list-style-type:none">\n	<li><strong>Reliability:</strong>&nbsp;Reliability is one of the most crucial demands from the UPS. Even clients who want to save money and are prepared to settle for a third grade system, will still search for the promise of as high a MTBF as they can find. What is reliability when it comes to the UPS? Continuous provision of power to the load. the objective is to keep the system running on inverter even in case of a fault. without transferring to bypass like it would in a common system.</li>\n	<li><strong>Size and Weight:</strong>&nbsp;As far as weight and size are concerned, there is a big advantage to a system without transformers and power chokes. The smaller and lighter the system the cheaper the shipment and storage are. Furthermore, if the client is interested in a redundant UPS, a modular system with one extra module will be at least twice as small as two regular parallel redundant UPS systems.</li>\n	<li><strong>Efficiency:</strong>&nbsp;Since modular systems are inevitably without transformers, one can reach the highest efficiency possible &ndash; up to 96%.</li>\n	<li><strong>Repair time and spare parts:</strong>&nbsp;The common consensus is that technicians prefer to work with systems that are made up of modules. Most repairs can be done by replacing the module. When it comes to modular systems the MTTR is low, spare parts are available and similar in different systems. These advantages are very meaningful to distributors.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3>In Conclusion</h3>\n\n<p>Even though much more can be said on this topic, the emphasize here is clear: Modular UPS systems have many benefits over the standard ones, starting from the basics regarding reliability and efficiency and up to the benefits of size and weight.</p>\n\n<p>(Contribution of Leon Vak &amp; Omer Halivni)</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h2>Modular UPS Systems</h2>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Modular UPS systems are designed to provide stable and accurate voltage to systems whose operation are critical and are dependable on such a reliable supply. The UPS system requirements focus on many parameters and in every situation reliable supply remains the ultimate requirement.</p>\n\n<h3>This requirement means UPS systems must also have the following structured requirements:</h3>\n\n<ol>\n	<li><strong>Performance</strong>: The ability to provide stable supplies despite possible changes in the electric grid caused by problems of voltage, frequency and waveform characterized by networks and complex power lines, and of course providing the steady energy required to supply in all load conditions including power over surge, surge power fluctuations and the absence of grid power supply from independent batteries during disaster recovery.&nbsp; &nbsp;Performance has minimum specification requirements including demands arising from the quality of system, such as: efficiency, floor space, volume, weight, and acoustic noise. Among other performance gains it&rsquo;s possible to point achievement to the power density&nbsp;that enables receiving high power&nbsp;in small floor space. And all this at a low weight which allows M_kVA250 supply system on regular flooring due to the small load is made possible by advanced technology.&nbsp;The technology achievements&nbsp;are reflected&nbsp;in software, hardware,&nbsp;heat transfer,&nbsp;mechanical&nbsp;packaging&nbsp;and of course&nbsp;nice&nbsp;and&nbsp;easy access and high-level&nbsp;Human&nbsp;Engineering.&nbsp;The system contains&nbsp;parallel&nbsp;modules&nbsp;that allow&nbsp;the power distribution of&nbsp;current&nbsp;flow according to the number of modules&nbsp;at the entrance,&nbsp;exit&nbsp;and&nbsp;battery loading, so there is an equal&nbsp;loading on each&nbsp;module.&nbsp;Entry&nbsp;system contains a&nbsp;Charger provider&nbsp;with&nbsp;the ability&nbsp;to&nbsp;receive a&nbsp;sinusoidal&nbsp;stream&nbsp;and&nbsp;phase&nbsp;with the&nbsp;grid voltage&nbsp;which allows&nbsp;receiving&nbsp;PF-1&nbsp;and especially low THD&nbsp;harmonic distortions.&nbsp;Input&nbsp;stream&nbsp;is&nbsp;minimal&nbsp;one-PF which&nbsp;allows&nbsp;lowering&nbsp;entrance&nbsp;cables&nbsp;and&nbsp;reducing&nbsp;feed stock&nbsp;supply.Port&nbsp;system is a&nbsp;sinusoidal&nbsp;voltage&nbsp;and the&nbsp;system allows&nbsp;the loading of&nbsp;non-linear&nbsp;load&nbsp;with&nbsp;FC&nbsp;as high as&nbsp;six.</li>\n	<li><strong>Reliability and availability</strong>&nbsp;of power supply&nbsp;the demand&nbsp;for which&nbsp;has grown&nbsp;to require the availability of&nbsp;&rdquo;six&nbsp;nines&rdquo; that is0.999999. Reliability is required despite the dynamics resulting from the networks and frequently changing loads and sometimes unpredictable behavior. The Highest reliability is used in&nbsp;Double Conversion True Online work meaning batteries that are connected to the regular exit and input converter with no transition downtime during power outages.</li>\n	<li><strong>Green energy</strong>&nbsp;received&nbsp;by&nbsp;high efficiency&nbsp;means&nbsp;improved technology&nbsp;and precise planning.&nbsp;Current&nbsp;efficiency&nbsp;UPS&nbsp;systems&nbsp;now exceed the&nbsp;96%&nbsp;which means&nbsp;only 4% of&nbsp;losses,&nbsp;versus&nbsp;previous&nbsp;generation&nbsp;systems&nbsp;whose efficiency&nbsp;was around&nbsp;90-92%.</li>\n	<li><strong>Redundancy</strong>:&nbsp;Redundancy&nbsp;is required&nbsp;from your&nbsp;UPS&nbsp;unit&nbsp;so that a single fault&nbsp;will&nbsp;allow&nbsp;work&nbsp;to continue&nbsp;without a hitch.Redundancy&nbsp;is possible&nbsp;by&nbsp;parallel&nbsp;systems&nbsp;work.</li>\n</ol>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<h3>Modular UPS system advantages are immediate parameters:</h3>\n\n<ol>\n	<li>Can&nbsp;grow with&nbsp;power&nbsp;as required&nbsp;and as a result&nbsp;minimal&nbsp;expense&nbsp;of purchase.&nbsp;Of course&nbsp;this is a&nbsp;savings of&nbsp;working hours&nbsp;and physical labor&nbsp;required&nbsp;and upgrading the device.</li>\n	<li>Possibility to&nbsp;replace&nbsp;a faulty&nbsp;module&nbsp;during hitch &ndash; APC.&nbsp;Compared with&nbsp;normal system&nbsp;repair&nbsp;which&nbsp;requires&nbsp;disabling&nbsp;as&nbsp;when replacing&nbsp;a module,&nbsp;the system continues&nbsp;to function&nbsp;without&nbsp;disabling&nbsp;at&nbsp;all.</li>\n	<li>Opportunity to receive&nbsp;redundancy&nbsp;in a simple and&nbsp;immediate&nbsp;manner&nbsp;as&nbsp;any failure&nbsp;by&nbsp;one of the&nbsp;N?&nbsp;Modules&nbsp;still&nbsp;allows regular supply&nbsp;load.&nbsp;Work method and&nbsp;N+ allows&nbsp;a dramatic&nbsp;increase in&nbsp;reliability&nbsp;since it&nbsp;